{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17657491","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17657491"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:29:15+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:29:15+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20501"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"20501","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/20501"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0,0.05,0.05,0,0.91]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13374"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92604"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13374","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13374"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20501"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75944"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"11582"},{"type":"tags","id":"11753"},{"type":"tags","id":"12432"},{"type":"tags","id":"12433"},{"type":"tags","id":"12795"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"31730"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31731"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92604","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/92604"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003ECholesterol metabolism is tightly regulated in normal cells to prevent intracellular accumulation. \u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the pathophysiology of foam cell formation in atherosclerosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Increased degradation of cholesterol by lysosomal enzymes","Reduced uptake of low-density lipoproteins by vascular cells","Formation of cholesterol crystals within hepatocytes","Decreased synthesis of cell membrane cholesterol","Accumulation of cholesterol esters in macrophages and smooth muscle cells"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe pathophysiology of atherosclerosis involves \u003Cstrong\u003Eaccumulation of cholesterol esters in macrophages and smooth muscle cells\u003C/strong\u003E within the intimal layer of arteries. These lipid-laden cells develop a foamy appearance and are called foam cells. When these foam cells aggregate, they form the characteristic yellow cholesterol-laden atheromas seen in atherosclerosis. Some foam cells may rupture, releasing their contents into the extracellular space where cholesterol can form crystals that appear as needle-like clefts in tissue sections.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained as follows:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDecreased synthesis of cell membrane cholesterol\u003C/strong\u003E - This is not a feature of atherosclerosis. In fact, there is excessive cholesterol accumulation rather than decreased synthesis.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased degradation of cholesterol by lysosomal enzymes\u003C/strong\u003E - In atherosclerosis, there is impaired metabolism of cholesterol rather than increased degradation.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFormation of cholesterol crystals within hepatocytes\u003C/strong\u003E - While cholesterol crystals do form in atherosclerosis, they occur in the arterial walls after foam cell rupture, not within hepatocytes.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReduced uptake of low-density lipoproteins by vascular cells\u003C/strong\u003E - Atherosclerosis actually involves increased uptake of modified LDL by macrophages via scavenger receptors, not reduced uptake.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFoam cell formation is not unique to atherosclerosis and can also be seen in other conditions such as xanthomas (in hyperlipidemic states), cholesterolosis (in the gallbladder lamina propria), and Niemann-Pick disease type C (due to mutations affecting cholesterol trafficking).\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Cholesterol esters accumulate intracellularly when normal cholesterol metabolism is disrupted, forming foam cells with vacuolated appearance.","Foam cells are characteristic of atherosclerosis, xanthomas, cholesterolosis, and Niemann-Pick disease type C.","Extracellular cholesterol crystals form when foam cells rupture, creating needle-like structures and clefts in tissue sections."],"references":["Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020. p. 62-63."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75944"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20501"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75944","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/75944"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-18T14:43:13+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-18T14:44:27+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13374"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92604"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11582","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11582"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Cell injury, cell death and adaptations","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":1,"createdAt":"2025-02-26T15:12:31+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-26T15:12:31+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"18"}},"headin